nt to cache<br />the key itself (and hide it in private_data or similar rather than<br />look it up, but if looking it up by uid is ok, then file-&gt;f_cred is<br />ok.<br /><br />And if you check permissions at IO time (again using file-&gt;f_cred),<br />that's ok from a kernel perspective, but it's not really<br />POSIX-compliant. But obviously a lot of netrwork filesystems aren't<br />posix-compliant anyway.<br /><br />                  Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
